{"title_page": "Boria Majumdar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n'''Boria Majumdar''' is an Indian sports journalist, academician and author.\n\nMajumdar was born on 8 March 1976 at [[Kolkata]]. He completed his schooling from [[The Frank Anthony Public School, Kolkata]]. He completed BA & MA in history from [[University of Calcutta]]. He was awarded [[Doctor of Philosophy|DPhil]] in History from [[University of Oxford]] in 2004 where he was [[Rhodes Scholarship|Rhodes scholar]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.uclan.ac.uk/staff_profiles/professor_boria_majumdar.php|title=Professor Boria Majumdar {{!}} Staff Profile {{!}}University of Central Lancashire|website=UCLan - University of Central Lancashire|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldwhoswho.com/public/views/entry.html?id=sl2170547|title=Majumdar Boria : World Who's Who|website=www.worldwhoswho.com|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\nHe co-authored [[Playing It My Way]], the autobiography of former [[India]]n [[cricketer]] [[Sachin Tendulkar]] along with [[Sachin Tendulkar|Sachin]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://www.amazon.com/Playing-It-My-Way-Autobiography/dp/1473605202 | title=Playing It My Way: My Autobiography | first1=Boria | last1=Majumdar | first2=Sachin | last2=Tendulkar | date=6 November 2014 | publisher=Hodder & Stoughton | isbn=978-1473605206 | accessdate=26 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 his second book, ''Eleven Gods and a Billion Indians: The On and Off the Field Story of Cricket in India and Beyond'', was published by Simon & Schuster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/books/review-eleven-gods-and-a-billion-indians-by-boria-majumdar/story-FmxAVDfMllZoV0nhDDAaVL.html|title=Review: Eleven Gods and a Billion Indians by Boria Majumdar|last=Sen|first=Sudeep|date=2018-05-25|website=hindustantimes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he is senior research fellow in the School of Sport and Wellbeing at the University of Central Lancashire.<ref name=\":0\" /> Previously he has worked as distinguished visiting fellow at La Trobe University, Melbourne and, since 2003, as visiting lecturer at the University of Chicago.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nMajumdar is married to Sharmistha Gupta.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n* [http://www.boriamajumdar.com/ Official website]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Majumdar, Boria}}\n[[Category:Indian sports journalists]]\n[[Category:University of Calcutta alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n\n\n{{India-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n'''Boria Majumdar''' is an Indian sports journalist, academician and author.\n\nMajumdar was born on 8 March 1976 at [[Kolkata]]. He completed his schooling from [[The Frank Anthony Public School, Kolkata]]. He completed BA & MA in history from [[University of Calcutta]]. He was awarded [[Doctor of Philosophy|DPhil]] in History from [[University of Oxford]] in 2004 where he was [[Rhodes Scholarship|Rhodes scholar]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.uclan.ac.uk/staff_profiles/professor_boria_majumdar.php|title=Professor Boria Majumdar {{!}} Staff Profile {{!}}University of Central Lancashire|website=UCLan - University of Central Lancashire|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldwhoswho.com/public/views/entry.html?id=sl2170547|title=Majumdar Boria : World Who's Who|website=www.worldwhoswho.com|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\nHe co-authored [[Playing It My Way]], the autobiography of former [[India]]n [[cricketer]] [[Sachin Tendulkar]] along with [[Sachin Tendulkar|Sachin]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://www.amazon.com/Playing-It-My-Way-Autobiography/dp/1473605202 | title=Playing It My Way: My Autobiograph